# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: iec-61850
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] An **electric power system** is a network of electrical components deployed to supply, transfer, and use electric power.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] An example of a power system is the electrical grid that provides power to homes and industries within an extended area.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The electrical grid can be broadly divided into the generators that supply the power, the transmission system that carries the power from the generating centers to the load centers, and the distribution system that feeds the power to nearby homes and industries.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Smaller power systems are also found in industry, hospitals, commercial buildings, and homes.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] A single line diagram helps to represent this whole system.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The majority of these systems rely upon three-phase AC power—the standard for large-scale power transmission and distribution across the modern world.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Specialized power systems that do not always rely upon three-phase AC power are found in aircraft, electric rail systems, ocean liners, submarines, and automobiles.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In 1889, two electricians built the world's first power system at Godalming in England.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] It was powered by two water wheels and produced an alternating current that in turn supplied seven Siemens arc lamps at 250 volts and 34 incandescent lamps at 40 volts.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] However, supply to the lamps was intermittent and in 1882 Thomas Edison and his company, Edison Electric Light Company, developed the first steam-powered electric power station on Pearl Street in New York City.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The Pearl Street Station initially powered around 3,000 lamps for 59 customers.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The power station generated direct current and operated at a single voltage.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Direct current power could not be transformed easily or efficiently to the higher voltages necessary to minimize power loss during long-distance transmission, so the maximum economic distance between the generators and load was limited to around half a mile (800 m).
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] That same year in London, Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs demonstrated the "secondary generator"—the first transformer suitable for use in a real power system.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The practical value of Gaulard and Gibbs' transformer was demonstrated in 1884 at Turin where the transformer was used to light up 40 kilometers (25 miles) of railway from a single alternating current generator.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Despite the success of the system, the pair made some fundamental mistakes.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Perhaps the most serious was connecting the primaries of the transformers in series so that active lamps would affect the brightness of other lamps further down the line.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In 1885, Ottó Titusz Bláthy working with Károly Zipernowsky and Miksa Déri perfected the secondary generator of Gaulard and Gibbs, providing it with a closed iron core and its present name: the "transformer".
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The system lit more than 1000 carbon filament lamps and operated successfully from May until November of that year.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Also in 1885 George Westinghouse, an American entrepreneur, obtained the patent rights to the Gaulard-Gibbs transformer and imported a number of them along with a Siemens generator, and set his engineers to experimenting with them in hopes of improving them for use in a commercial power system.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Using this knowledge he built a multi-voltage transformer-based alternating-current power system serving multiple homes and businesses at Great Barrington, Massachusetts in 1886.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The system was unreliable and short-lived, though, due primarily to generation issues.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] However, based on that system, Westinghouse would begin installing AC transformer systems in competition with the Edison Company later that year.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In 1888, Westinghouse licensed Nikola Tesla's patents for a polyphase AC induction motor and transformer designs.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Tesla consulted for a year at the Westinghouse Electric & Manufacturing Company but it took a further four years for Westinghouse engineers to develop a workable polyphase motor and transmission system.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] By 1889, the electric power industry was flourishing, and power companies had built thousands of power systems (both direct and alternating current) in the United States and Europe.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] These networks were effectively dedicated to providing electric lighting.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] During this time the rivalry between Thomas Edison and George Westinghouse's companies had grown into a propaganda campaign over which form of transmission (direct or alternating current) was superior, a series of events known as the "war of the currents".
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In 1891, Westinghouse installed the first major power system that was designed to drive a 100 horsepower (75 kW) synchronous electric motor, as well as provide electric lighting, at Telluride, Colorado.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In the United States the AC/DC competition came to an end when Edison General Electric was taken over by their chief AC rival, the Thomson-Houston Electric Company, forming General Electric.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In 1895, after a protracted decision-making process, alternating current was chosen as the transmission standard with Westinghouse building the Adams No.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] 1 generating station at Niagara Falls and General Electric building the three-phase alternating current power system to supply Buffalo at 11 kV.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Developments in power systems continued beyond the nineteenth century.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In 1936 the first experimental high voltage direct current (HVDC) line using mercury arc valves was built between Schenectady and Mechanicville, New York.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] HVDC had previously been achieved by series-connected direct current generators and motors (the Thury system) although this suffered from serious reliability issues.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The first solid-state metal diode suitable for general power uses was developed by Ernst Presser at TeKaDe in 1928.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] It consisted of a layer of selenium applied on an aluminum plate.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In 1957, a General Electric research group developed the first thyristor suitable for use in power applications, starting a revolution in power electronics.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In that same year, Siemens demonstrated a solid-state rectifier, but it was not until the early 1970s that solid-state devices became the standard in HVDC, when GE emerged as one of the top suppliers of thyristor-based HVDC.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In 1979, a European consortium including Siemens, Brown Boveri & Cie and AEG realized the record HVDC link from Cabora Bassa to Johannesburg, extending more than 1,420 kilometers (880 miles) that carried 1.9 GW at 533 kV.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In recent times, many important developments have come from extending innovations in the information and communications technology (ICT) field to the power engineering field.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] For example, the development of computers meant load flow studies could be run more efficiently, allowing for much better planning of power systems.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Advances in information technology and telecommunication also allowed for effective remote control of a power system's switchgear and generators.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Electric power is the product of two quantities: current and voltage.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] These two quantities can vary with respect to time (AC power) or can be kept at constant levels (DC power).
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Most refrigerators, air conditioners, pumps and industrial machinery use AC power, whereas most computers and digital equipment use DC power (digital devices plugged into the mains typically have an internal or external power adapter to convert from AC to DC power).
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] AC power has the advantage of being easy to transform between voltages and is able to be generated and utilised by brushless machinery.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] DC power remains the only practical choice in digital systems and can be more economical to transmit over long distances at very high voltages (see HVDC).
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The ability to easily transform the voltage of AC power is important for two reasons: firstly, power can be transmitted over long distances with less loss at higher voltages.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] So in power systems where generation is distant from the load, it is desirable to step-up (increase) the voltage of power at the generation point and then step-down (decrease) the voltage near the load.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Secondly, it is often more economical to install turbines that produce higher voltages than would be used by most appliances, so the ability to easily transform voltages means this mismatch between voltages can be easily managed.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Solid-state devices, which are products of the semiconductor revolution, make it possible to transform DC power to different voltages, build brushless DC machines and convert between AC and DC power.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Nevertheless, devices utilising solid-state technology are often more expensive than their traditional counterparts, so AC power remains in widespread use.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] All power systems have one or more sources of power.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] For some power systems, the source of power is external to the system but for others, it is part of the system itself—it is these internal power sources that are discussed in the remainder of this section.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Direct current power can be supplied by batteries, fuel cells or photovoltaic cells.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Alternating current power is typically supplied by a rotor that spins in a magnetic field in a device known as a turbo generator.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] There have been a wide range of techniques used to spin a turbine's rotor, from steam heated using fossil fuel (including coal, gas and oil) or nuclear energy to falling water (hydroelectric power) and wind (wind power).
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The speed at which the rotor spins in combination with the number of generator poles determines the frequency of the alternating current produced by the generator.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] All generators on a single synchronous system, for example, the national grid, rotate at sub-multiples of the same speed and so generate electric current at the same frequency.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] If the load on the system increases, the generators will require more torque to spin at that speed and, in a steam power station, more steam must be supplied to the turbines driving them.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Thus the steam used and the fuel expended directly relate to the quantity of electrical energy supplied.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] An exception exists for generators incorporating power electronics such as gearless wind turbines or linked to a grid through an asynchronous tie such as a HVDC link — these can operate at frequencies independent of the power system frequency.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Depending on how the poles are fed, alternating current generators can produce a variable number of phases of power.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] A higher number of phases leads to more efficient power system operation but also increases the infrastructure requirements of the system.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Electricity grid systems connect multiple generators operating at the same frequency: the most common being three-phase at 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] There are a range of design considerations for power supplies.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] These range from the obvious: How much power should the generator be able to supply?
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] What is an acceptable length of time for starting the generator (some generators can take hours to start)?
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Is the availability of the power source acceptable (some renewables are only available when the sun is shining or the wind is blowing)?
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] To the more technical: How should the generator start (some turbines act like a motor to bring themselves up to speed in which case they need an appropriate starting circuit)?
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] What is the mechanical speed of operation for the turbine and consequently what are the number of poles required?
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] What type of generator is suitable (synchronous or asynchronous) and what type of rotor (squirrel-cage rotor, wound rotor, salient pole rotor or cylindrical rotor)?
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Power systems deliver energy to loads that perform a function.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] These loads range from household appliances to industrial machinery.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Most loads expect a certain voltage and, for alternating current devices, a certain frequency and number of phases.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The appliances found in residential settings, for example, will typically be single-phase operating at 50 or 60 Hz with a voltage between 110 and 260 volts (depending on national standards).
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] An exception exists for larger centralized air conditioning systems as these are now often three-phase because this allows them to operate more efficiently.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] All electrical appliances also have a wattage rating, which specifies the amount of power the device consumes.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] At any one time, the net amount of power consumed by the loads on a power system must equal the net amount of power produced by the supplies less the power lost in transmission.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Making sure that the voltage, frequency and amount of power supplied to the loads is in line with expectations is one of the great challenges of power system engineering.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] A final consideration with loads has to do with power quality.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In addition to sustained overvoltages and undervoltages (voltage regulation issues) as well as sustained deviations from the system frequency (frequency regulation issues), power system loads can be adversely affected by a range of temporal issues.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] These include voltage sags, dips and swells, transient overvoltages, flicker, high-frequency noise, phase imbalance and poor power factor.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Power quality issues occur when the power supply to a load deviates from the ideal.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Power quality issues can be especially important when it comes to specialist industrial machinery or hospital equipment.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Conductors carry power from the generators to the load.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Choice of conductors is based on considerations such as cost, transmission losses and other desirable characteristics of the metal like tensile strength.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Copper, with lower resistivity than aluminum, was once the conductor of choice for most power systems.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] However, aluminum has a lower cost for the same current carrying capacity and is now often the conductor of choice.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Overhead line conductors may be reinforced with steel or aluminium alloys.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Conductors in exterior power systems may be placed overhead or underground.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Overhead conductors are usually air insulated and supported on porcelain, glass or polymer insulators.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Cables used for underground transmission or building wiring are insulated with cross-linked polyethylene or other flexible insulation.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Conductors are often stranded for to make them more flexible and therefore easier to install.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Conductors are typically rated for the maximum current that they can carry at a given temperature rise over ambient conditions.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] As current flow increases through a conductor it heats up.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] For insulated conductors, the rating is determined by the insulation.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] For bare conductors, the rating is determined by the point at which the sag of the conductors would become unacceptable.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The majority of the load in a typical AC power system is inductive; the current lags behind the voltage.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Since the voltage and current are out-of-phase, this leads to the emergence of reactive power.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Reactive power does no measurable work but is transmitted back and forth between the reactive power source and load every cycle.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Reactors consume reactive power and are used to regulate voltage on long transmission lines.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In light load conditions, where the loading on transmission lines is well below the surge impedance loading, the efficiency of the power system may actually be improved by switching in reactors.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Reactors installed in series in a power system also limit rushes of current flow, small reactors are therefore almost always installed in series with capacitors to limit the current rush associated with switching in a capacitor.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Series reactors can also be used to limit fault currents.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Capacitors and reactors are switched by circuit breakers, which results in sizeable step changes of reactive power.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] A solution to this comes in the form of synchronous condensers, static VAR compensators and static synchronous compensators.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Briefly, synchronous condensers are synchronous motors that spin freely to generate or absorb reactive power.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Static VAR compensators work by switching in capacitors using thyristors as opposed to circuit breakers allowing capacitors to be switched-in and switched-out within a single cycle.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] This provides a far more refined response than circuit-breaker-switched capacitors.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Static synchronous compensators take this a step further by achieving reactive power adjustments using only power electronics.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Power electronics are semiconductor based devices that are able to switch quantities of power ranging from a few hundred watts to several hundred megawatts.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Despite their relatively simple function, their speed of operation (typically in the order of nanoseconds) means they are capable of a wide range of tasks that would be difficult or impossible with conventional technology.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The classic function of power electronics is rectification, or the conversion of AC-to-DC power, power electronics are therefore found in almost every digital device that is supplied from an AC source either as an adapter that plugs into the wall (see photo) or as component internal to the device.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] High-powered power electronics can also be used to convert AC power to DC power for long distance transmission in a system known as HVDC.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] HVDC is used because it proves to be more economical than similar high voltage AC systems for very long distances (hundreds to thousands of kilometres).
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] HVDC is also desirable for interconnects because it allows frequency independence thus improving system stability.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Power electronics are also essential for any power source that is required to produce an AC output but that by its nature produces a DC output.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] They are therefore used by photovoltaic installations.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Power electronics are also found in practically all modern petrol-powered vehicles, this is because the power provided by the car's batteries alone is insufficient to provide ignition, air-conditioning, internal lighting, radio and dashboard displays for the life of the car.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] So the batteries must be recharged while driving—a feat that is typically accomplished using power electronics.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Some electric railway systems also use DC power and thus make use of power electronics to feed grid power to the locomotives and often for speed control of the locomotive's motor.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In the middle twentieth century, rectifier locomotives were popular, these used power electronics to convert AC power from the railway network for use by a DC motor.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Today most electric locomotives are supplied with AC power and run using AC motors, but still use power electronics to provide suitable motor control.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The use of power electronics to assist with the motor control and with starter circuits, in addition to rectification, is responsible for power electronics appearing in a wide range of industrial machinery.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Power electronics even appear in modern residential air conditioners allow are at the heart of the variable speed wind turbine.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Power systems contain protective devices to prevent injury or damage during failures.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The quintessential protective device is the fuse.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] When the current through a fuse exceeds a certain threshold, the fuse element melts, producing an arc across the resulting gap that is then extinguished, interrupting the circuit.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Given that fuses can be built as the weak point of a system, fuses are ideal for protecting circuitry from damage.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Fuses however have two problems: First, after they have functioned, fuses must be replaced as they cannot be reset.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] This can prove inconvenient if the fuse is at a remote site or a spare fuse is not on hand.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] And second, fuses are typically inadequate as the sole safety device in most power systems as they allow current flows well in excess of that that would prove lethal to a human or animal.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The first problem is resolved by the use of circuit breakers—devices that can be reset after they have broken current flow.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In modern systems that use less than about 10 kW, miniature circuit breakers are typically used.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] These devices combine the mechanism that initiates the trip (by sensing excess current) as well as the mechanism that breaks the current flow in a single unit.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Some miniature circuit breakers operate solely on the basis of electromagnetism.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In these miniature circuit breakers, the current is run through a solenoid, and, in the event of excess current flow, the magnetic pull of the solenoid is sufficient to force open the circuit breaker's contacts (often indirectly through a tripping mechanism).
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In higher powered applications, the protective relays that detect a fault and initiate a trip are separate from the circuit breaker.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Early relays worked based upon electromagnetic principles similar to those mentioned in the previous paragraph, modern relays are application-specific computers that determine whether to trip based upon readings from the power system.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Different relays will initiate trips depending upon different protection schemes.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] For example, an overcurrent relay might initiate a trip if the current on any phase exceeds a certain threshold whereas a set of differential relays might initiate a trip if the sum of currents between them indicates there may be current leaking to earth.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The circuit breakers in higher powered applications are different too.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Air is typically no longer sufficient to quench the arc that forms when the contacts are forced open so a variety of techniques are used.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] One of the most popular techniques is to keep the chamber enclosing the contacts flooded with sulfur hexafluoride (SF6)—a non-toxic gas with sound arc-quenching properties.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Other techniques are discussed in the reference.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The second problem, the inadequacy of fuses to act as the sole safety device in most power systems, is probably best resolved by the use of residual-current devices (RCDs).
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In any properly functioning electrical appliance, the current flowing into the appliance on the active line should equal the current flowing out of the appliance on the neutral line.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] A residual current device works by monitoring the active and neutral lines and tripping the active line if it notices a difference.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Residual current devices require a separate neutral line for each phase and to be able to trip within a time frame before harm occurs.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Even with the installation of an RCD, exposure to electricity can still prove fatal.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In large electric power systems, supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) is used for tasks such as switching on generators, controlling generator output and switching in or out system elements for maintenance.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The first supervisory control systems implemented consisted of a panel of lamps and switches at a central console near the controlled plant.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The lamps provided feedback on the state of the plant (the data acquisition function) and the switches allowed adjustments to the plant to be made (the supervisory control function).
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Today, SCADA systems are much more sophisticated and, due to advances in communication systems, the consoles controlling the plant no longer need to be near the plant itself.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Instead, it is now common for plants to be controlled with equipment similar (if not identical) to a desktop computer.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The ability to control such plants through computers has increased the need for security—there have already been reports of cyber-attacks on such systems causing significant disruptions to power systems.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Despite their common components, power systems vary widely both with respect to their design and how they operate.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] This section introduces some common power system types and briefly explains their operation.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Residential dwellings almost always take supply from the low voltage distribution lines or cables that run past the dwelling.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] These operate at voltages of between 110 and 260 volts (phase-to-earth) depending upon national standards.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] A few decades ago small dwellings would be fed a single phase using a dedicated two-core service cable (one core for the active phase and one core for the neutral return).
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The active line would then be run through a main isolating switch in the fuse box and then split into one or more circuits to feed lighting and appliances inside the house.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] By convention, the lighting and appliance circuits are kept separate so the failure of an appliance does not leave the dwelling's occupants in the dark.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] All circuits would be fused with an appropriate fuse based upon the wire size used for that circuit.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Circuits would have both an active and neutral wire with both the lighting and power sockets being connected in parallel.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Sockets would also be provided with a protective earth.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] This would be made available to appliances to connect to any metallic casing.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] If this casing were to become live, the theory is the connection to earth would cause an RCD or fuse to trip—thus preventing the future electrocution of an occupant handling the appliance.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Earthing systems vary between regions, but in countries such as the United Kingdom and Australia both the protective earth and neutral line would be earthed together near the fuse box before the main isolating switch and the neutral earthed once again back at the distribution transformer.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] There have been a number of minor changes over the years to practice of residential wiring.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Commercial power systems such as shopping centers or high-rise buildings are larger in scale than residential systems.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Electrical designs for larger commercial systems are usually studied for load flow, short-circuit fault levels and voltage drop.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The objectives of the studies are to assure proper equipment and conductor sizing, and to coordinate protective devices so that minimal disruption is caused when a fault is cleared.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Large commercial installations will have an orderly system of sub-panels, separate from the main distribution board to allow for better system protection and more efficient electrical installation.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Typically one of the largest appliances connected to a commercial power system in hot climates is the HVAC unit, and ensuring this unit is adequately supplied is an important consideration in commercial power systems.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Regulations for commercial establishments place other requirements on commercial systems that are not placed on residential systems.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] For example, in Australia, commercial systems must comply with AS 2293, the standard for emergency lighting, which requires emergency lighting be maintained for at least 90 minutes in the event of loss of mains supply.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In the United States, the National Electrical Code requires commercial systems to be built with at least one 20 A sign outlet in order to light outdoor signage.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Building code regulations may place special requirements on the electrical system for emergency lighting, evacuation, emergency power, smoke control and fire protection.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Power system management varies depending upon the power system.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Residential power systems and even automotive electrical systems are often run-to-fail.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In aviation, the power system uses redundancy to ensure availability.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] On the Boeing 747-400 any of the four engines can provide power and circuit breakers are checked as part of power-up (a tripped circuit breaker indicating a fault).
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Larger power systems require active management.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In industrial plants or mining sites a single team might be responsible for fault management, augmentation and maintenance.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Where as for the electric grid, management is divided amongst several specialised teams.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Fault management involves monitoring the behaviour of the power system so as to identify and correct issues that affect the system's reliability.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Fault management can be specific and reactive: for example, dispatching a team to restring conductor that has been brought down during a storm.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Or, alternatively, can focus on systemic improvements: such as the installation of reclosers on sections of the system that are subject to frequent temporary disruptions (as might be caused by vegetation, lightning or wildlife).
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In addition to fault management, power systems may require maintenance or augmentation.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] As often it is neither economical nor practical for large parts of the system to be offline during this work, power systems are built with many switches.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] These switches allow the part of the system being worked on to be isolated while the rest of the system remains live.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] At high voltages, there are two switches of note: isolators and circuit breakers.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Circuit breakers are load-breaking switches where as operating isolators under load would lead to unacceptable and dangerous arcing.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] In a typical planned outage, several circuit breakers are tripped to allow the isolators to be switched before the circuit breakers are again closed to reroute power around the isolated area.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] This allows work to be completed on the isolated area.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Beyond fault management and maintenance one of the main difficulties in power systems is that the active power consumed plus losses must equal the active power produced.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] If load is reduced while generation inputs remain constant the synchronous generators will spin faster and the system frequency will rise.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] The opposite occurs if load is increased.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] As such the system frequency must be actively managed primarily through switching on and off dispatchable loads and generation.
[src:iec-61850/electric-power-system] Making sure the frequency is constant is usually the task of a system operator.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] A **substation** is a part of an electrical generation, transmission, and distribution system.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Substations transform voltage from high to low, or the reverse, or perform any of several other important functions.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Between the generating station and the consumer, electric power may flow through several substations at different voltage levels.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] A substation may include transformers to change voltage levels between high transmission voltages and lower distribution voltages, or at the interconnection of two different transmission voltages.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] They are a common component of the infrastructure.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] As of 2002, there were approximately 55,000 substations in the United States.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Substations are also occasionally known in some countries as **switchyards**.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Substations may be owned and operated by an electrical utility, or may be owned by a large industrial or commercial customer.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Generally substations are unattended, relying on SCADA for remote supervision and control.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] The word *substation* comes from the days before the distribution system became a grid.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] As central generation stations became larger, smaller generating plants were converted to distribution stations, receiving their energy supply from a larger plant instead of using their own generators.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] The first substations were connected to only one power station, where the generators were housed, and were subsidiaries of that power station.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Substations may be designed and built by a contractor or alternately all phases of its development may be handled by the electrical utility.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Most commonly, the utility does the engineering and procurement while hiring a contractor for actual construction.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Major design constraints for construction of substations include land availability and cost, limitations on the construction period, transportation restrictions, and the need to get the substation running quickly.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Prefabrication is a common way to reduce the construction cost.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] For connecting the new substation, a partial outage at another substation may be required, but the utility often tries to minimize downtime.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] A *transmission substation* connects two or more transmission lines.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] The simplest case is where all transmission lines have the same voltage.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] In such cases, substation contains high-voltage switches that allow lines to be connected or isolated for fault clearance or maintenance.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Transmission substations can range from simple to complex.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] A small "switching station" may be little more than a bus plus some circuit breakers.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] The largest transmission substations can cover a large area (several acres/hectares) with multiple voltage levels, many circuit breakers, and a large amount of protection and control equipment (voltage and current transformers, relays and SCADA systems).
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Modern substations may be implemented using international standards such as IEC Standard 61850.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] A *distribution substation* transfers power from the transmission system to the distribution system of an area.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] It is uneconomical to directly connect electricity consumers to the main transmission network, unless they use large amounts of power, so the distribution station reduces voltage to a level suitable for local distribution.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] The input for a distribution substation is typically at least two transmission or sub-transmission lines.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Input voltage may be, for example, 115 kV, or whatever is common in the area.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Distribution voltages are typically medium voltage, between 2.4 kV and 33 kV, depending on the size of the area served and the practices of the local utility.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] The feeders run along streets overhead (or underground, in some cases) and power the distribution transformers at or near the customer premises.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] In addition to transforming voltage, distribution substations also isolate faults in either the transmission or distribution systems.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Distribution substations are typically the points of voltage regulation, although on long distribution circuits (of several miles/kilometers), voltage regulation equipment may also be installed along the line.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] The downtown areas of large cities feature complicated distribution substations, with high-voltage switching, and switching and backup systems on the low-voltage side.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] More typical distribution substations have a switch, one transformer, and minimal facilities on the low-voltage side.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] In distributed generation projects such as a wind farm or photovoltaic power station, a collector substation may be required.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] It resembles a distribution substation although power flow is in the opposite direction, from many wind turbines or inverters up into the transmission grid.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Usually for economy of construction the collector system operates around 35 kV, although some collector systems are 12 kV, and the collector substation steps up voltage to a transmission voltage for the grid.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] The collector substation can also provide power factor correction if it is needed, metering, and control of the wind farm.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] In some special cases a collector substation can also contain an HVDC converter station.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Collector substations also exist where multiple thermal or hydroelectric power plants of comparable output power are in proximity.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Examples for such substations are Brauweiler in Germany and Hradec in the Czech Republic, where power is collected from nearby lignite-fired power plants.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] If no transformers are required for increasing the voltage to transmission level, the substation is a switching station.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Converter substations may be associated with HVDC converter plants, traction current, or interconnected non-synchronous networks.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] These stations contain power electronic devices to change the frequency of current, or else convert from alternating to direct current or the reverse.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Formerly rotary converters changed frequency to interconnect two systems; nowadays such substations are rare.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] A switching station is a substation without transformers and operating only at a single voltage level.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Switching stations are sometimes used as collector and distribution stations.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Sometimes they are used for switching the current to back-up lines or for parallelizing circuits in case of failure.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] An example is the switching stations for the Inga–Shaba HVDC transmission line.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] A switching station may also be known as a switchyard, and these are commonly located directly adjacent to or nearby a power station.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] In this case the generators from the power station supply their power into the yard onto the generator bus on one side of the yard, and the transmission lines take their power from a Feeder Bus on the other side of the yard.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] An important function performed by a substation is switching, which is the connecting and disconnecting of transmission lines or other components to and from the system.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Switching events may be planned or unplanned.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] A transmission line or other component may need to be de-energized for maintenance or for new construction, for example, adding or removing a transmission line or a transformer.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] To maintain reliability of supply, companies aim at keeping the system up and running while performing maintenance.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] All work to be performed, from routine testing to adding entirely new substations, should be done while keeping the whole system running.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] The function of the switching station is to isolate the faulty portion of the system in the shortest possible time.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] De-energizing faulty equipment protects it from further damage, and isolating a fault helps keep the rest of the electrical grid operating with stability.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Electrified railways also use substations, often distribution substations.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] In some cases a conversion of the current type takes place, commonly with rectifiers for direct current (DC) trains, or rotary converters for trains using alternating current (AC) at frequencies other than that of the public grid.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Sometimes they are also transmission substations or collector substations if the railway network also operates its own grid and generators to supply the other stations.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] A *mobile substation* is a substation on wheels, containing a transformer, breakers and buswork mounted on a self-contained semi-trailer, meant to be pulled by a truck.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] They are designed to be compact for travel on public roads, and are used for temporary backup in times of natural disaster or war.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Mobile substations are usually rated much lower than permanent installations, and may be built in several units to meet road travel limitations.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Substation design is aimed at minimizing cost while ensuring power availability and reliability, and enabling changes to the substation in the future.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Substations may be built outdoors, indoors, or underground or in a combination of these locations.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Selection of the location of a substation must consider many factors.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Sufficient land area is required for installation of equipment with necessary clearances for electrical safety, and for access to maintain large apparatus such as transformers.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] The site must have room for expansion due to load growth or planned transmission additions.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Environmental effects of the substation must be considered, such as drainage, noise and road traffic effects.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] The substation site must be reasonably central to the distribution area to be served.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] The site must be secure from intrusion by passers-by, both to protect people from injury by electric shock or arcs, and to protect the electrical system from misoperation due to vandalism.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] If not owned and operated by a utility company, substations are typically occupied on a long lease such as a renewable 99-year lease, giving the utility company security of tenure.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] The first step in planning a substation layout is the preparation of a single-line diagram, which shows in simplified form the switching and protection arrangement required, as well as the incoming supply lines and outgoing feeders or transmission lines.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] It is a usual practice by many electrical utilities to prepare one-line diagrams with principal elements (lines, switches, circuit breakers, transformers) arranged on the page similarly to the way the apparatus would be laid out in the actual station.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] In a common design, incoming lines have a disconnector and a circuit breaker.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] In some cases, the lines will not have both, with either a switch or a circuit breaker being all that is considered necessary.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] A disconnect switch is used to provide isolation, since it cannot interrupt load current.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] A circuit breaker is used as a protection device to interrupt fault currents automatically, and may be used to switch loads on and off, or to cut off a line when power is flowing in the 'wrong' direction.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] When a large fault current flows through the circuit breaker, this is detected through the use of current transformers.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] The magnitude of the current transformer outputs may be used to trip the circuit breaker resulting in a disconnection of the load supplied by the circuit break from the feeding point.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] This seeks to isolate the fault point from the rest of the system, and allow the rest of the system to continue operating with minimal impact.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Both switches and circuit breakers may be operated locally (within the substation) or remotely from a supervisory control center.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] With overhead transmission lines, the propagation of lightning and switching surges can cause insulation failures into substation equipment.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Line entrance surge arrestors are used to protect substation equipment accordingly.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Insulation Coordination studies are carried out extensively to ensure equipment failure (and associated outages) is minimal.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Once past the switching components, the lines of a given voltage connect to one or more buses.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] These are sets of busbars, usually in multiples of three, since three-phase electrical power distribution is largely universal around the world.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] The arrangement of switches, circuit breakers, and buses used affects the cost and reliability of the substation.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] For important substations a ring bus, double bus, or so-called "breaker and a half" setup can be used, so that the failure of any one circuit breaker does not interrupt power to other circuits, and so that parts of the substation may be de-energized for maintenance and repairs.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Substations feeding only a single industrial load may have minimal switching provisions, especially for small installations.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Because of the risk of electrical shock, substations are inherently dangerous to electrical workers.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] To mitigate this hazard, substations are designed with various safety features.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Live conductors and bare equipment are kept separate, either with protected equipment, or using screens or distance.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] To this is added the necessary space for employees to work safely and vehicles to pass.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Sometimes it is necessary to work on parts of the substation while energized, but employees must maintain a safe distance of at least 3 metres (9.8 ft).
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] The aim to reduce substation footprints comes into conflict with ease of maintenance enhanced by including gaps where employees can safely work.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Underneath a substation, a mat or grid of conductors laid around 0.5 or 0.6 metres (1 ft 8 in or 2 ft 0 in) underground provides grounding.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] This grid, which is typically copper although it may be galvanized iron in some countries, is used to ground circuits that are being worked on to prevent accidental re-energization while workers are in contact with a de-energized circuit.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Often, earth rods are driven deeper into the ground from the grounding grid for lower resistance grounding, and may be surrounded by bentonite or marconite to further reduce resistance and ensure effective grounding for the lifetime of the substation.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Above ground, the grounding conductors may be steel, aluminum, or copper.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] They must be thick enough to carry the expected current of a fault for 1–3 seconds and remain undamaged.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Substation fences, typically at least 2 metres (6 ft 7 in) in height, both protect the public from electrical hazards and also protect the substation from vandalism.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Internal fences can also be incorporated to protect employees from areas that are unsafe when energized.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Substations generally have switching, protection and control equipment, and transformers.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] In a large substation, circuit breakers are used to interrupt any short circuits or overload currents that may occur on the network.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Smaller distribution stations may use recloser circuit breakers or fuses for protection of distribution circuits.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Substations themselves do not usually have generators, although a power plant may have a substation nearby.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Other devices such as capacitors, voltage regulators, and reactors may also be located at a substation.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Substations may be on the surface in fenced enclosures, underground, or special-purpose buildings.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] High-rise buildings may have several indoor substations.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Indoor substations are usually found in urban areas to reduce the noise from transformers, improve appearance, or protect switchgear from extreme climate or pollution.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Substations often use busbars as conductors between electrical equipment.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Busbars may be aluminum tubing 3–6 inches (76–152 mm) thick, or else wires (strain bus).
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Outdoor, above-ground substation structures include wood pole, lattice metal tower, and tubular metal structures, although other variants are available.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Where space is plentiful and appearance of the station is not a factor, steel lattice towers provide low-cost supports for transmission lines and apparatus.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Low-profile substations may be specified in suburban areas where appearance is more critical.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Indoor substations may be gas insulated substations (GIS) (at high voltages, with gas insulated switchgear), or use metal-enclosed or metal-clad switchgear at lower voltages.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Urban and suburban indoor substations may be finished on the outside so as to blend in with other buildings in the area.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] A *compact substation* is generally an outdoor substation built in a metal enclosure, in which each item of the electrical equipment is located very near to each other to create a relatively smaller footprint size of the substation.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] High-voltage circuit breakers are commonly used to interrupt the flow of current in substation equipment.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] At the time of interruption, current could be normal, too high due to excessive load, unusual due to a fault, or tripped by protective relays prior to anticipated trouble.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Reclosers are similar to breakers, and can be cheaper because they do not require separate protective relays.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Often used in distribution, they often are programmed to trip when the amps exceed a certain amount over a period of time.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Reclosers will attempt to re-energize the circuit after a delay.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] If unsuccessful for a few times, the recloser will have to be manually reset by an electrical worker.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Capacitor banks are used in substations to balance the lagging current draw from inductive loads (such as motors, transformers, and some industrial equipment) with their reactive load.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Additional capacitor capacity may be needed if dispersed generation (such as small diesel generators, rooftop photovoltaic solar panels, or wind turbines) are added to the system.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Capacitors can reduce the current in wires, helping stem system losses from voltage drop or enabling extra power to be sent through the conductors.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Capacitors may be left on in response to constant inductive load or turned on when inductive load is increased, such as in the summer for air conditioners.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] The switching may be remote and can be done manually or automatically.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Larger substations have control rooms for the equipment used to monitor, control, and protect the rest of the substation equipment.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] It often contains protective relays, meters, breaker controls, communications, batteries, and recorders that save detailed data about substation operations, particularly when there is any unusual activity, to help reconstruct what happened after the fact.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] These control rooms typically are heated and air conditioned to ensure the reliable operation of this equipment.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Additional equipment is necessary to handle power surges associated with intermittent renewable energy such as dispersed generation from wind or solar.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Most transformers lose between 5 and 1.5 percent of their input as heat and noise.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Iron losses are no-load and constant whenever the transformer is energized, while copper and auxiliary losses are proportionate to the square of the current.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Auxiliary losses are due to running fans and pumps which is noisy when the transformer is operating at maximum capacity.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] To reduce noise, enclosures are often built around the transformer and can also be added after the substation is built.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Oil-based transformers are often built with bunded areas to prevent the escape of flaming or leaking oil.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Fire separation areas or firewalls are built around the transformer to stop the spread of fire.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Firefighting vehicles are allowed a path to access the area.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Maintenance of substations involves inspections, data collection and analysis, and routine scheduled work.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Using methods such as infrared scanning and dissolved gas analysis, it can be predicted when the substation will need maintenance and predict dangers before they materialize.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Infrared technology finds hot spots in the substation where electrical energy is being converted to heat, which indicates a problem and can cause additional damage from the high heat.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Dissolved gas analysis can tell when an oil-insulated transformer needs to have the oil filtered or replaced, and also detect other issues.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Early electrical substations required manual switching or adjustment of equipment, and manual collection of data for load, energy consumption, and abnormal events.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] As the complexity of distribution networks grew, it became economically necessary to automate supervision and control of substations from a centrally attended point, to allow overall coordination in case of emergencies and to reduce operating costs.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Early efforts to remote control substations used dedicated communication wires, often run alongside power circuits.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Power-line carrier, microwave radio, fiber optic cables as well as dedicated wired remote control circuits have all been applied to Supervisory Control and Data Acquisition (SCADA) for substations.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] The development of the microprocessor made for an exponential increase in the number of points that could be economically controlled and monitored.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Today, standardized communication protocols such as DNP3, IEC 61850 and Modbus, to list a few, are used to allow multiple intelligent electronic devices to communicate with each other and supervisory control centers.
[src:iec-61850/electrical-substation] Distributed automatic control at substations is one element of the so-called smart grid.
[src:iec-61850/intelligent-electronic-device] In the electric power industry, an **intelligent electronic device** (**IED**) is an integrated microprocessor-based controller of power system equipment, such as circuit breakers, transformers and capacitor banks.
[src:iec-61850/intelligent-electronic-device] IEDs receive data from sensors and power equipment and can issue control commands, such as tripping circuit breakers if they sense voltage, current, or frequency anomalies, or raise/lower tap positions in order to maintain the desired voltage level.
[src:iec-61850/intelligent-electronic-device] Common types of IEDs include protective relaying devices, tap changer controllers, circuit breaker controllers, capacitor bank switches, recloser controllers, voltage regulators etc.
[src:iec-61850/intelligent-electronic-device] This is generally controlled by a setting file.
[src:iec-61850/intelligent-electronic-device] The testing of setting files is typically one of the most time-consuming roles of a protection tester.
[src:iec-61850/intelligent-electronic-device] Digital protective relays are primarily IEDs, using a microprocessor to perform several protective, control and similar functions.
[src:iec-61850/intelligent-electronic-device] Some recent IEDs are designed to support the IEC61850 standard for substation automation, which provides interoperability and advanced communications capabilities.
[src:iec-61850/intelligent-electronic-device] IEDs are used as a more modern alternative to, or a complement of, setup with traditional remote terminal units (RTUs).
[src:iec-61850/intelligent-electronic-device] Unlike the RTUs, IEDs are integrated with the devices they control and offer a standardized set of measuring and control points that is easier to configure and require less wiring.
[src:iec-61850/intelligent-electronic-device] Most IEDs have a communication port and built-in support for standard communication protocols (DNP3, IEC104 or IEC 61850), so they can communicate directly with the SCADA system or a substation programmable logic controller.
[src:iec-61850/intelligent-electronic-device] Alternatively, they can be connected to a substation RTU that acts as a gateway towards the SCADA server.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] In electrical engineering, a **protective relay** is a relay device designed to trip a circuit breaker when a fault is detected.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The first protective relays were electromagnetic devices, relying on coils operating on moving parts to provide detection of abnormal operating conditions such as over-current, overvoltage, reverse power flow, over-frequency, and under-frequency.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Microprocessor-based solid-state digital protection relays now emulate the original devices, as well as providing types of protection and supervision impractical with electromechanical relays.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Electromechanical relays provide only rudimentary indication of the location and origin of a fault.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] In many cases a single microprocessor relay provides functions that would take two or more electromechanical devices.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] By combining several functions in one case, numerical relays also save capital cost and maintenance cost over electromechanical relays.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] However, due to their very long life span, tens of thousands of these "silent sentinels" are still protecting transmission lines and electrical apparatus all over the world.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Important transmission lines and generators have cubicles dedicated to protection, with many individual electromechanical devices, or one or two microprocessor relays.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The theory and application of these protective devices is an important part of the education of a power engineer who specializes in power system protection.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The need to act quickly to protect circuits and equipment often requires protective relays to respond and trip a breaker within a few thousandths of a second.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] In some instances these clearance times are prescribed in legislation or operating rules.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] A maintenance or testing program is used to determine the performance and availability of protection systems.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Based on the end application and applicable legislation, various standards such as ANSI C37.90, IEC255-4, IEC60255-3, and IAC govern the response time of the relay to the fault conditions that may occur.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Electromechanical protective relays operate by either magnetic attraction, or magnetic induction.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Unlike switching type electromechanical relays with fixed and usually ill-defined operating voltage thresholds and operating times, protective relays have well-established, selectable, and adjustable time and current (or other operating parameter) operating characteristics.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Protection relays may use arrays of induction disks, shaded-pole, magnets, operating and restraint coils, solenoid-type operators, telephone-relay contacts, and phase-shifting networks.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Protective relays can also be classified by the type of measurement they make.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] A protective relay may respond to the magnitude of a quantity such as voltage or current.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Induction relays can respond to the product of two quantities in two field coils, which could for example represent the power in a circuit.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] "It is not practical to make a relay that develops a torque equal to the quotient of two a.c. quantities.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Several operating coils can be used to provide "bias" to the relay, allowing the sensitivity of response in one circuit to be controlled by another.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Various combinations of "operate torque" and "restraint torque" can be produced in the relay.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] By use of a permanent magnet in the magnetic circuit, a relay can be made to respond to current in one direction differently from in another.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Such polarized relays are used on direct-current circuits to detect, for example, reverse current into a generator.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] These relays can be made bistable, maintaining a contact closed with no coil current and requiring reverse current to reset.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] For AC circuits, the principle is extended with a polarizing winding connected to a reference voltage source.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Lightweight contacts make for sensitive relays that operate quickly, but small contacts can't carry or break heavy currents.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Often the measuring relay will trigger auxiliary telephone-type armature relays.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] In a large installation of electromechanical relays, it would be difficult to determine which device originated the signal that tripped the circuit.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] This information is useful to operating personnel to determine the likely cause of the fault and to prevent its re-occurrence.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Relays may be fitted with a "target" or "flag" unit, which is released when the relay operates, to display a distinctive colored signal when the relay has tripped.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] "Armature"-type relays have a pivoted lever supported on a hinge or knife-edge pivot, which carries a moving contact.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] These relays may work on either alternating or direct current, but for alternating current, a shading coil on the pole is used to maintain contact force throughout the alternating current cycle.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Because the air gap between the fixed coil and the moving armature becomes much smaller when the relay has operated, the current required to maintain the relay closed is much smaller than the current to first operate it.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The "returning ratio" or "differential" is the measure of how much the current must be reduced to reset the relay.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] A variant application of the attraction principle is the plunger-type or solenoid operator.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] A reed relay is another example of the attraction principle.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] "Moving coil" meters use a loop of wire turns in a stationary magnet, similar to a galvanometer but with a contact lever instead of a pointer.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] These can be made with very high sensitivity.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Another type of moving coil suspends the coil from two conductive ligaments, allowing very long travel of the coil.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] "Induction" disk meters work by inducing currents in a disk that is free to rotate; the rotary motion of the disk operates a contact.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Induction relays require alternating current; if two or more coils are used, they must be at the same frequency otherwise no net operating force is produced.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] These electromagnetic relays use the induction principle discovered by Galileo Ferraris in the late 19th century.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The magnetic system in induction disc overcurrent relays is designed to detect overcurrents in a power system and operate with a pre-determined time delay when certain overcurrent limits have been reached.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The following important conclusions can be drawn from the above equation.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The relay's primary winding is supplied from the power systems current transformer via a plug bridge, which is called the plug setting multiplier (psm).
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Usually seven equally spaced tappings or operating bands determine the relays sensitivity.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The primary winding is located on the upper electromagnet.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The secondary winding has connections on the upper electromagnet that are energised from the primary winding and connected to the lower electromagnet.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Once the upper and lower electromagnets are energised they produce eddy currents that are induced onto the metal disc and flow through the flux paths.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] This relationship of eddy currents and fluxes creates torque proportional to the input current of the primary winding, due to the two flux paths being out of phase by 90°.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] In an overcurrent condition, a value of current will be reached that overcomes the control spring pressure on the spindle and the braking magnet, causing the metal disc to rotate towards the fixed contact.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] This initial movement of the disc is also held off to a critical positive value of current by small slots that are often cut into the side of the disc.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The time taken for rotation to make the contacts is not only dependent on current but also the spindle backstop position, known as the time multiplier (tm).
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The time multiplier is divided into 10 linear divisions of the full rotation time.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Providing the relay is free from dirt, the metal disc and the spindle with its contact will reach the fixed contact, thus sending a signal to trip and isolate the circuit, within its designed time and current specifications.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Drop off current of the relay is much lower than its operating value, and once reached the relay will be reset in a reverse motion by the pressure of the control spring governed by the braking magnet.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Application of electronic amplifiers to protective relays was described as early as 1928, using vacuum tube amplifiers and continued up to 1956.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Devices using electron tubes were studied but never applied as commercial products, because of the limitations of vacuum tube amplifiers.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] A relatively large standby current is required to maintain the tube filament temperature; inconvenient high voltages are required for the circuits, and vacuum tube amplifiers had difficulty with incorrect operation due to noise disturbances.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Static relays have no or few moving parts, and became practical with the introduction of the transistor.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Measuring elements of static relays have been successfully and economically built up from diodes, zener diodes, avalanche diodes, unijunction transistors, p-n-p and n-p-n bipolar transistors, field effect transistors or their combinations.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Static relays offer the advantage of higher sensitivity than purely electromechanical relays, because power to operate output contacts is derived from a separate supply, not from the signal circuits.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Static relays eliminated or reduced contact bounce, and could provide fast operation, long life and low maintenance.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Digital protective relays were in their infancy during the late 1960s.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] An experimental digital protection system was tested in the lab and in the field in the early 1970s.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Unlike the relays mentioned above, digital protective relays have two main parts: hardware and software.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The world's first commercially available digital protective relay was introduced to the power industry in 1984 by Schweitzer Engineering Laboratories (SEL) based in Pullman, Washington.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] In spite of the developments of complex algorithms for implementing protection functions the microprocessor based-relays marketed in the 1980s did not incorporate them.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] A microprocessor-based digital protection relay can replace the functions of many discrete electromechanical instruments.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] These relays convert voltage and currents to digital form and process the resulting measurements using a microprocessor.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The digital relay can emulate functions of many discrete electromechanical relays in one device, simplifying protection design and maintenance.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Each digital relay can run self-test routines to confirm its readiness and alarm if a fault is detected.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Digital relays can also provide functions such as communications (SCADA) interface, monitoring of contact inputs, metering, waveform analysis, and other useful features.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Digital relays can, for example, store multiple sets of protection parameters, which allows the behavior of the relay to be changed during maintenance of attached equipment.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Digital relays also can provide protection strategies impossible to implement with electromechanical relays.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] This is particularly so in long-distance high voltage or multi-terminal circuits or in lines that are series or shunt compensated They also offer benefits in self-testing and communication to supervisory control systems.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The distinction between digital and numerical protection relay rests on points of fine technical detail, and is rarely found in areas other than Protection.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Numerical relays are the product of the advances in technology from digital relays.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Generally, there are several different types of numerical protection relays.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Each type, however, shares a similar architecture, thus enabling designers to build an entire system solution that is based on a relatively small number of flexible components.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] They use high speed processors executing appropriate algorithms.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Most numerical relays are also multifunctional and have multiple setting groups each often with tens or hundreds of settings.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The various protective functions available on a given relay are denoted by standard ANSI device numbers.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] For example, a relay including function 51 would be a timed overcurrent protective relay.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] An **overcurrent relay** is a type of protective relay which operates when the load current exceeds a pickup value.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] It is of two types: instantaneous over current (IOC) relay and definite time overcurrent (DTOC) relay.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The ANSI device number is 50 for an IOC relay or a DTOC relay.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] In a typical application, the over current relay is connected to a current transformer and calibrated to operate at or above a specific current level.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] When the relay operates, one or more contacts will operate and energize to trip a circuit breaker.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The DTOC relay has been used extensively in the United Kingdom but its inherent issue of operating slower for faults closer to the source led to the development of the IDMT relay.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] A **definite time over-current (DTOC) relay** is a relay that operates after a definite period of time once the current exceeds the pickup value.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Hence, this relay has current setting range as well as time setting range.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] An **instantaneous over-current relay** is an overcurrent relay which has no intentional time delay for operation.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The contacts of the relay are closed instantly when the current inside the relay rises beyond the operational value.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The time interval between the instant pick-up value and the closing contacts of the relay is very low.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] It has low operating time and starts operating instantly when the value of current is more than the relay setting.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] This relay operates only when the impedance between the source and the relay is less than that provided in the section.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] An **inverse-time over-current (ITOC) relay** is an overcurrent relay which operates only when the magnitude of their operating current is inversely proportional to the magnitude of the energize quantities.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The operating time of relay decreases with the increases in the current.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The operation of the relay depends on the magnitude of the current.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] An **inverse definite minimum time (IDMT) relay** is a protective relay which is developed to overcome the shortcomings of the definite time overcurrent (DTOC) relays.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] If the source impedance remains constant and the fault current changes appreciably as we move away from the relay then it is advantageous to use IDMT overcurrent protection to achieve high speed protection over a large section of the protected circuit.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] However, if the source impedance is significantly larger than the feeder impedance then the characteristic of the IDMT relay cannot be exploited and DTOC may be utilized.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Secondly if the source impedance varies and becomes weaker with less generation during light loads then this leads to slower clearance time hence negating the purpose of the IDMT relay.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] IEC standard 60255-151 specifies the IDMT relay curves as shown below.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The four curves in Table 1 are derived from the now withdrawn British Standard BS 142.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The other five, in Table 2, are derived from the ANSI standard C37.112.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] While it is more common to use IDMT relays for current protection it is possible to utilize IDMT mode of operation for voltage protection.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] It is possible to program customised curves in some protective relays and other manufacturers have special curves specific to their relays.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Some numerical relays can be used to provide inverse time overvoltage protection or negative sequence overcurrent protection.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Ir = is the ratio of the fault current to the relay setting current or a Plug Setting Multiplier.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] "Plug" is a reference from the electromechanical relay era and were available in discrete steps.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The above equations result in a "family" of curves as a result of using different time multiplier setting (TMS) settings.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] It is evident from the relay characteristic equations that a larger TMS will result in a slower clearance time for a given PMS (Ir) value.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] A differential scheme acts on the difference between current entering a protected zone (which may be a bus bar, generator, transformer or other apparatus) and the current leaving that zone.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] A fault outside the zone gives the same fault current at the entry and exit of the zone, but faults within the zone show up as a difference in current.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] "The differential protection is 100% selective and therefore only responds to faults within its protected zone.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The boundary of the protected zone is uniquely defined by the location of the current transformers.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Time grading with other protection systems is therefore not required, allowing for tripping without additional delay.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Differential protection can be used to provide protection for zones with multiple terminals and can be used to protect lines, generators, motors, transformers, and other electrical plant.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] A **directional relay** uses an additional polarizing source of voltage or current to determine the direction of a fault.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Directional elements respond to the phase shift between a polarizing quantity and an operate quantity.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] The fault can be located upstream or downstream of the relay's location, allowing appropriate protective devices to be operated inside or outside of the zone of protection.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] A synchronism checking relay provides a contact closure when the frequency and phase of two sources are similar to within some tolerance margin.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] A "synch check" relay is often applied where two power systems are interconnected, such as at a switchyard connecting two power grids, or at a generator circuit breaker to ensure the generator is synchronized to the system before connecting it.
[src:iec-61850/protective-relay] Relays can also be classified by their type of power source.
